<common-name datatype='string'>folD-ybcJ</common-name>
<comment datatype='string'>Putative promoter islands, which are regions of DNA containing multiple transcription start sites, were found by computational prediction methods in the intergenic region of the &lt;i&gt;folD&lt;/i&gt; and &lt;i&gt;sfmA&lt;/i&gt; genes in &lt;i&gt;E. coli&lt;/i&gt;. These promoter islands are associated with genes acquired horizontally, and they are absent in the same region in &lt;i&gt;Salmonella&lt;/i&gt; [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23717391&quot;&gt;Panyukov13&lt;/a&gt;]. In addition, some sites that bind HNS have been predicted in this intergenic region. This protein appears to inactivate the promoter islands [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23717391&quot;&gt;Panyukov13&lt;/a&gt;].
&lt;p&gt;
The transcription of  the &lt;i&gt;ybcJ&lt;/i&gt; gene is induced during the first 24 h after the induction of nitrogen starvation [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/32571968&quot;&gt;Switzer20&lt;/a&gt;].</comment>
